risk.formattedText:
{{#paragraph}}Most sensitive applications in finance, commerce and other security intensive industries tend to specify session timeouts between 15 and 30 minutes.{{/paragraph}}

{{#paragraph}}Session timeouts greater than 30 minutes give attackers extra time to complete attacks and exploits. Specifically, overly long sessions make applications 
more susceptible to session hijacking and cross-user web attacks, such as Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) and Cross-Site Scripting (XSS).{{/paragraph}}

recommendation.formattedText:
{{#paragraph}}You have multiple options for decreasing the session timeout in your applications:{{/paragraph}}

{{#unorderedList}}
    {{#listElement}}{{#code}}/WEB-INF/web.xml{{/code}} file, as shown in this example:
       {{#xmlBlock}}
        <session-config>
          <session-timeout>30</session-timeout>
        </session-config>
       {{/xmlBlock}}    
    {{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}{{#code}}/META-INF/resources/web-fragment.xml{{/code}} in a JAR file that's inside a WAR file's {{#code}}/WEB-INF/lib{{/code}} folder{{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}For Java servlets, you have the option of using these methods
      {{#unorderedList}}
        {{#listElement}}{{#code}}ServletContext.setSessionTimeout(int){{/code}} {{#link}}https://javaee.github.io/javaee-spec/javadocs/javax/servlet/ServletContext.html#setSessionTimeout-int-$$LINK_DELIM$$Javadoc{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
        {{#listElement}}{{#code}}HttpSession.setMaxInactiveInterval(int){{/code}} {{#link}}https://javaee.github.io/javaee-spec/javadocs/javax/servlet/http/HttpSession.html#setMaxInactiveInterval-int-$$LINK_DELIM$$Javadoc{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
      {{/unorderedList}}
    {{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}If you are using the Spring framework, you have these options for setting the timeout value
      {{#unorderedList}}
        {{#listElement}}Spring Boot 1.x:
          {{#unorderedList}}
            {{#listElement}}The {{#code}}server.session.timeout{{/code}} property in {{#code}}application.properties{{/code}} or {{#code}}application.yaml{{/code}} file.{{/listElement}}
            {{#listElement}}{{#code}}ConfigurableEmbeddedServletContainer.setSessionTimeout(int, TimeUnit){{/code}}. {{#link}}https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/1.5.22.RELEASE/reference/html/boot-features-developing-web-applications.html#boot-features-programmatic-embedded-container-customization$$LINK_DELIM$$docs{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
          {{/unorderedList}}
        {{/listElement}}
        {{#listElement}}Spring Boot 2.x:
          {{#unorderedList}}
            {{#listElement}}The {{#code}}server.servlet.session.timeout{{/code}} property in {{#code}}application.properties{{/code}} or {{#code}}application.yaml{{/code}} file.{{/listElement}}
            {{#listElement}}Customize the server with {{#code}}ConfigurableServletWebServerFactory{{/code}}. {{#link}}https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/2.3.1.RELEASE/reference/html/howto.html#howto-configure-webserver$$LINK_DELIM$$docs{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
            {{#listElement}}{{#code}}SessionProperties.setTimeout(Duration){{/code}}. {{#link}}https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/api/org/springframework/boot/autoconfigure/session/SessionProperties.html#setTimeout-java.time.Duration-$$LINK_DELIM$$docs{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
          {{/unorderedList}}
        {{/listElement}}
        {{#listElement}}Spring Session 1.x:
          {{#unorderedList}}
            {{#listElement}}{{#code}}ExpiringSession.setMaxInactiveIntervalInSeconds(int){{/code}}. {{#link}}https://docs.spring.io/spring-session/docs/1.3.5.RELEASE/api/org/springframework/session/ExpiringSession.html#setMaxInactiveIntervalInSeconds-int-$$LINK_DELIM$$docs{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
            {{#listElement}}{{#code}}SessionRepository.setDefaultMaxInactiveInterval(int){{/code}}. {{#link}}https://docs.spring.io/spring-session/docs/1.3.5.RELEASE/api/org/springframework/session/MapSessionRepository.html#setDefaultMaxInactiveInterval-int-$$LINK_DELIM$$docs{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
          {{/unorderedList}}
        {{/listElement}}
        {{#listElement}}Spring Session 2.x:
          {{#unorderedList}}
            {{#listElement}}The {{#code}}spring.session.timeout{{/code}} property in {{#code}}application.properties{{/code}} or {{#code}}application.yaml{{/code}} file.{{/listElement}}
            {{#listElement}}{{#code}}Session.setMaxInactiveInterval(Duration){{/code}}. {{#link}}https://docs.spring.io/spring-session/docs/2.3.1.RELEASE/api/org/springframework/session/Session.html#setMaxInactiveInterval-java.time.Duration-$$LINK_DELIM$$docs{{/link}}{{/listElement}}
          {{/unorderedList}}
        {{/listElement}}
      {{/unorderedList}}
    {{/listElement}}

{{/unorderedList}}


{{#paragraph}}Most critical applications tend to have timeouts in the 15-30 minute range. As such, Contrast expects to see a value less than or equal to 30 minutes. Your value should depend on how your users use the application. Consider the following questions when deciding your timeout value:{{/paragraph}}

{{#unorderedList}}
    {{#listElement}}Do your users use this application from work, home or both?{{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}Would a user use this application from a kiosk? A friend's computer?{{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}Is there financial incentive for a random person who stumbles upon a user's logged in session?{{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}How critical is this application to the business? To your users' life or well-being?{{/listElement}}
{{/unorderedList}}

