{{#paragraph}}Any {{#code}}&lt;form&gt;{{/code}} tags without the {{#code}}autocomplete{{/code}} attribute set to {{#code}}off{{/code}} allow user
agents to automatically save user credentials. Even if individual fields have {{#code}}autocomplete{{/code}}
disabled, it is a safer practice to cover the entire {{#code}}&lt;form&gt;{{/code}}.
{{/paragraph}}

recommendation.formattedText:
{{#paragraph}}Disabling {{#code}}autocomplete{{/code}} on form values is easy. All you have to do is add an {{#code}}autocomplete{{/code}} attribute
with a setting of {{#code}}off{{/code}}, as is shown in the password field of this example:{{/paragraph}}

{{#htmlBlock}}
<form action="/login" method="POST">
    <input type="text" name="username">
    <input type="password" name="userpass" autocomplete="off">
</form>{{/htmlBlock}}

{{#paragraph}}However, to prevent Contrast from flagging the form, you should disable {{#code}}autocomplete{{/code}} on the entire
{{#code}}&lt;form&gt;{{/code}}, as shown here:{{/paragraph}}

{{#htmlBlock}}
<form action="/login" method="POST" autocomplete="off">
    <input type="text" name="username">
    <input type="password" name="userpass">
</form>{{/htmlBlock}}

risk.formattedText:
{{#paragraph}}The application doesn't apply anti-framing controls to the given page. Not applying these controls will allow it to be
framed by other websites. This can present a few security issues, but the chief concern is that framed pages may be used in
Clickjacking attacks.{{/paragraph}}

{{#paragraph}}Clickjacking (also called UI Redress) is an attack whereby an attacker can trick a user into clicking on something different
from what it appears they are clicking on. Most attacks will first build a page that entices the user to click on it - for scandalous
pictures, monetary rewards, and other promises. The buttons and links on this page are carefully placed so that they overlap with
buttons, links or other items on a second page that gets layered on top of the first one.{{/paragraph}}

{{#paragraph}}The problem for the victim in this scenario is that the link that they'd like to click for the promised rewards on the evil page
 is actually "beneath" a translucent, second page which has been framed into the HTML document. Thus, when they intend to click
 on {{#exampleText}}"Collect Your Prize!"{{/exampleText}}, they're really clicking on {{#exampleText}}Transfer Your Money!{{/exampleText}}, or similar.{{/paragraph}}

{{#paragraph}}Numerous real-life Clickjacking attacks have caused damage to Adobe Flash Player, and numerous websites including Facebook,
Twitter, YouTube, and others.{{/paragraph}}

{{#paragraph}}{{#code}}X-Frame-Options{{/code}} header can be used to prevent framing of a web page. Details about this control can be found in the {{#focus}}How to fix{{/focus}} tab.{{#badConfig}}This anti-framing control was not found{{/badConfig}} in the HTTP response.{{/paragraph}}

recommendation.formattedText:
{{#header}}Using the X-Frame-Options header{{/header}}
{{#paragraph}}All major modern browsers honor a header, called {{#code}}X-Frame-Options{{/code}}. This header instructs browsers about a page's preferences regarding being framed. Not setting this header has no effect, which means that the page is allowed to be framed from any web site. There are 3 possible values that can help restrict framing:{{/paragraph}}

{{#unorderedList}}
    {{#listElement}}{{#code}}DENY{{/code}}. When set to DENY, no pages may frame this page.{{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}{{#code}}SAMEORIGIN{{/code}}. When set to SAMEORIGIN, any page outside the origin of the hosting page may not frame this resource.{{/listElement}}
    {{#listElement}}{{#code}}ALLOW-FROM [URI]{{/code}}. The ALLOW-FROM setting, supported by Internet Explorer and Firefox, allows a URI to frame the given content. It's not known if this feature will eventually be adopted by Chrome, Safari, or other WebKit-based browsers. However, because numerous browsers don't support ALLOW-FROM, and it breaks X-Frame-Options in those browsers (meaning it allows any site to frame those pages), we recommend avoiding the use of ALLOW-FROM.{{/listElement}}
{{/unorderedList}}

{{#paragraph}}If Contrast sees a setting of X-Frame-Options of {{#code}}DENY{{/code}} or {{#code}}SAMEORIGIN{{/code}}, it will not report this issue.{{/paragraph}}

{{#paragraph}}There are a couple ways in the HTTP response to tell the browser and any intervening proxies to not cache this data. Given the
ever increasing number of browser and proxy version permutations, keeping up to date with what browser or proxy requires
what cache control is hard, and thus our recommendation is to issue a combination of caching controls in
order to properly inform user agents of different types of the application's intentions.
{{/paragraph}}
{{#paragraph}}
Issuing only a subset of these controls guarantees that some version of some browser or proxy will retain the page data when it shouldn't.
{{/paragraph}}

{{#paragraph}}The easiest way to prevent this issue from occurring in Java EE applications is to add these
{{#code}}setHeader(){{/code}} calls to a servlet filter for all sensitive content:
{{/paragraph}}
{{#javaBlock}}response.setHeader("Cache-Control","no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate"); //HTTP 1.1 controls
response.setHeader("Pragma","no-cache"); //HTTP 1.0 controls
response.setDateHeader("Expires", -1); //Prevents caching on proxy servers {{/javaBlock}}





{{#paragraph}}If setting headers is difficult in your infrastructure, you can also simulate them via
{{#code}}meta{{/code}} tags in the HTML sent to the browser:{{/paragraph}}

{{#xmlBlock}}<meta http-equiv="Cache-Control" content="no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate">
<meta http-equiv="Pragma" content="no-cache">
<meta http-equiv="Expires" content="-1"> {{/xmlBlock}}

{{#paragraph}}At a minimum, Contrast expects to see a {{#code}}Cache-Control{{/code}} setting that contains
{{#code}}no-store{{/code}} and {{#code}}no-cache{{/code}}. This will alleviate client-side browser caching
concerns in modern browsers. This control can be delivered with a {{#code}}setHeader(){{/code}} call or
a {{#code}}&lt;meta&gt;{{/code}} tag.{{/paragraph}}

